VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
REASON: Confirmed by inspection of src/fault_decode.rs: classify() at lines 357-368 branches only on (hfsr & HFSR_FORCED)!=0 || (hfsr & HFSR_VECTTBL)!=0, so hfsr=0x8000_0000 (HFSR.DEBUGEVT alone) with cfsr=0 falls through to the final else and returns FaultCategory::None. The Verus ensures block at lines 348-351 explicitly promises None for (hfsr & (HFSR_FORCED|HFSR_VECTTBL))==0 && cfsr==0, which the DEBUGEVT input satisfies — so the report's lemma_debugevt_alone_is_hardfault will fail Verus against the current spec, and the runtime PoC's assert_eq! will fail at runtime. The spec contradicts ARMv7-M B3.2.16 and upstream Zephyr's arch/arm/core/cortex_m/fault.c hard_fault() at line 731, which explicitly treats SCB_HFSR_DEBUGEVT_Msk as a HardFault source. It also contradicts the plain-English text of SWREQ-FD-FH01 ("if any fault status bits are set in CFSR or HFSR, classify returns non-None"). ARMv7-M cortex_m3 is the declared target (verification.yaml ubiquitously cites qemu_cortex_m3), so this is not an out-of-scope hardware config; the debug monitor disabled in production is a configuration assumption, not a declared caller precondition. Interestingness: real (contradicts the ARM ARM, upstream behavior, and the stated req), and proof-code drift is exactly the class of ASIL-D issue that matters. UCA mapping: gale's STPA artifact (artifacts/stpa.yaml) only covers Step 1a/1b/1c (Losses, Hazards, System Constraints); no UCAs exist for the fault-decode control action, and safety/stpa/ucas.yaml does not exist. A new UCA would be required, roughly: "UCA-FD-N: Fault handler provides FaultCategory::None classification when a HardFault exception is active (ARM ARM: any non-zero HFSR bit), causing the safety-logging/FTTI path to treat a real HardFault as no-fault — linked to H-? (new hazard: silent suppression of fault diagnostics) leading to L-1/L-2." Per the procedure, emitting a scenario is deferred until that UCA is approved.
